[[Category:new pages]][[Category:original pages]][[Category:new pages]][[Category:original pages]][[Category:new pages]][[Category:original pages]][[Category:new pages]][[Category:Prewar Japanese Holidays]] {{DEFAULTSORT:しゆくさいしつ}} [[Category:dd]] [[Category:bump]] [[ja:祝祭日]]

{{Otheruseslist|[[1948年]]7月19日以前の日本における祝祭日|[[1948年]]7月20日以降の日本における祝日|国民の祝日|その他の祝日|祝日|その他の祭日|祭日}}
Before July 19, 1948, in Japan, the term **"Shukusaijitsu"** (祝祭日) referred to **holidays** (祝日) and **festivals** (祭日) that were either regulated by custom or defined by law.
The term "Shukusaijitsu" generally refers to the combined holidays and festivals in Japan.
== Overview ==
=== Before the Azuchi-Momoyama Period === {{節スタブ|date=2019年4月2日 (火) 19:24 (UTC)}}
=== Edo Period === The following holidays and festivals existed. The **Five Seasonal Festivals** (五節句) are traditional **annual events** in Japanese culture derived from the Chinese **Yin-Yang Five Elements Theory**. These events were established as official ceremonies and holidays by the **Edo Shogunate**<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|和書|title=日建協：特集 祝日と日本人のお話|url=http://nikkenkyo.jp/before/back_number/compass781/08-09holiday/index.htm|website=nikkenkyo.jp|accessdate=2019-04-02|publisher=日本建設産業職員労働組合協議会}}</ref>. {{節スタブ|date=2019年4月2日 (火) 19:24 (UTC)}}
=== Meiji Period – Prewar Era === As part of the **national prestige policy** in the **Meiji Period**, traditional festivals such as the **Five Seasonal Festivals** were abolished and replaced with ceremonies promoting **State Shinto**<ref name=":0" />. The regulations were defined by: - The **"Regulations on Public Holidays"** ("年中祭日祝日ノ休暇日ヲ定ム"), issued under **Dajōkan Edict No. 344** in **1873** and later amended in **1878** and **1879**. - The **"Matters Concerning Public Holidays"** ("休日ニ関スル件"), issued under **Imperial Ordinance No. 19** in **1912** and revised in **1913** and **1927**.
Both holiday laws referred to these days as **festivals** (祭日) without using the term "Grand Festival Day" (大祭日). However, they were based on the **Great Festivals** (大祭) of **Imperial Household Rites**. Notably: - Annual festivals were included, except for certain **periodic festivals** (式年祭). - The **Kigensetsu Festival** (紀元節祭) and **Tenchōsetsu Festival** (天長節祭) were listed without "Festival" in their names, classified as holidays instead. - **Tenchōsetsu Festival** was the only minor festival (小祭). - Events like the **New Year Banquet** and **Meiji Setsu** were not Imperial Household Rites.
Due to the tradition of flying the **national flag** on these days, they were commonly called **"Flag Days"** (旗日) during the Meiji and Taishō periods.
On July 20, 1948, with the enactment of the **Public Holiday Law** ("国民の祝日に関する法律"), the **"Matters Concerning Public Holidays"** law was repealed.
