Both holiday laws referred to these days as '''festivals''' (祭日) without using the term "Grand Festival Day" (大祭日). However, they were based on the '''Great Festivals''' (大祭) of '''Imperial Household Rites'''. Notably: - Annual festivals were included, except for certain '''{{ill|Shikinen-sai|ja|式年祭|lt=periodic festivals}}''' (式年祭). - The '''Kigensetsu Festival''' (紀元節祭) and '''Tenchōsetsu Festival''' (天長節祭) were listed without "Festival" in their names, classified as holidays instead. - '''Tenchōsetsu Festival''' was the only minor festival (小祭). - Events like the '''New Year Banquet''' and '''Meiji Setsu''' were not Imperial Household Rites.
Due to the tradition of flying the '''national flag''' on these days, they were commonly called '''"Flag Days"''' (旗日) during the Meiji and Taishō periods.
On July 20, 1948, with the enactment of the '''Public Holiday Law''' ("国民の祝日に関する法律"), the '''"Matters Concerning Public Holidays"''' law was repealed.
